<br>
Feign Death is one of the two defining characteristics of the Monk class.  The other being the ability to Dual Wield at level one and having a higher skill cap in the skill than any other class.  This skill will be enormously important to playing a Monk well in most of the traditional roles a Monk plays in groups. It is also invaluable during soloing at higher levels.<br>
<br>
In a nutshell, the skill does two things.<br>
<br>
Causes you to be indifferent to all NPCs.   This means attacking NPCs stop attacking and will treat you as if you were invisible as long as you lie still.  This does not mean they will no longer attack you if you stand back up.  In that case it will be like you have lost your invisibility and you will again be attacked.<br>
<br>
Causes you to be removed from NPC "Hatelists" 100% of the time if the NPC is under level 32, and has a much smaller chance of removing you from the list if the NPC is above level 32.<br>
<br>
<H4>Getting and Training Feign Outside of Combat.</H4><br>
Feign Death is a trained skill.  This means visiting a Monk Trainer in one of the guilds is necessary to get the skill active after you reach level 17.<br>
<br>
From level 8 on I saved all my skill points. I spent 10 on Double Attack when I got it, but since I did a lot of soloing I did not anticipate many problems getting it to the level cap quickly/easily.  This meant I had 35 skill points(5 skill points per level saved up over 9 levels would be 45 points, but I spent 10 on Double Attack at level 15) I could give Feign Death a "jumpstart" with.  When I reached level 17, I spent all these points on Feign. This gave me a skill of 51 in Feign before I even left the guild hall. The first training point spent on a skill gained after level 1 gives you a skill level of the skill level your class gains that ability at and the others give you one skill point per training point.<br>
<br>
I immediately made a macro to train Feign Death during downtime and during travel.<br>
<br>
/doability 8 (my FD skill is in skill slot 8 )<br>
/stand<br>
/pause 90<br>
/doability 8<br>
/stand<br>
<br>
There may be better macros that could be contrived(and indeed others have replied to this thread with their favorites, I'll be including them as a small appendix at the end of this guide), but this one practices FD twice, and immediately stands back up after feigning.  This meant I could run and still use it as long as I was willing to forgo the use of the autorun feature.  Feigning and standing back up breaks the autorun and you would have to re-start it after each feign.  <br>
<br>
I used this macro as frequently as I possibly could.  The momentary hitch in your step as you fall and then stand back up adds minimal overhead to the length of time it takes to run most distances. It was even easier when I was on a boat. I'd use this macro and open up my abilities menu to practice Sense Heading, Sneak, Instill Doubt, etc on boat rides.  It is important to remember  that only one macro can execute at a time. So when I was using my Feign Death practice macro I could not use my macros to practice Sneak, Sense Heading, etc.  So I would have a bank of hotkeys with all these buttons in close proximity to my Feign Death practice macro. After I started the macro I would use the individual buttons to practice my other skills.  All of this could be done while traveling, and indeed I got many of my skill increases during my frequent runs across Antonica.<br>
<br>
As soon as I left the Ashen House in Freeport, I was dying to try out my new skill.  I ran out to the newbie area outside the gates in West Freeport and wasted several dozen shiruken pulling bats, rats, orcs, snakes, fire beetles, skeletons, pretty much anything I could hit, just to watch them get close to me before I would feign.  Very, very funny(and how ironic that this was good practice for splitting pulls later!).  <br>
<br>
I did some dumb things too.  I decided that the reason I was always able to feign off the greenies in the newbie zone was because they were green!  So I needed to try a harder target and see if they would buy it.   I got as far as I could from the Guard who patrols by the North  Freeport zone and threw a shiruken.<br>
<br>
LOADING, PLEASE WAIT<br>
You have LOST a level. You are now level 16.<br>
<br>
/cry<br>
<br>
I learned an important lesson with that death.  Different creatures have different chances to "believe" your trickery.   Those many levels higher than you will rarely "fall for it" and those many levels below you will almost always be fooled.<br>
<br>
I also did some silly things like being a Monk Flag hanging out over the guards by feigning as I stood on the edge of the wall of the city.  "Sleeping" in beds or "taking a nap in Emperor Crush's Throne" are still some of my favorite silly things to do. A female monk friend had a social emote made which she used to flirt with.<br>
<br>
/em faints at %Ts sexy eyes<br>
/doability Feign Death<br>
<br>
I thought it was funny the first time, but the death scream kind of ruined the mood :p       But the point holds, you can get in Feign Death practice even when you're doing silly things, and believe me, you can't practice enough.<br>
<br>
<H4>Using Feign Death to split spawns</H4><br>
I did not rely on FD during combat until my skill level hit the high 70s, and I was still very leary of it. If things started going bad, I would much rather turn tail and run, than attempt to Feign until my skill was very close to master level. Other monks have given the same impressions, failure to feign your death often results in your actual death at lower levels.<br>
<br>
Probably the first thing you should do when you start considering using FD during combat or to split pulls is to make a macro for it.  Here is what mine looks like.<br>
/autoattack off<br>
/doability 8 (Feign Death)<br>
/consider<br>
<br>
With autoattack still on, your feign is more likely to be unsuccessful.  This may be paranoia on the part of many monks, but it has long become habit and convention that FD is successful more often with the Autoattack turned off before the attempt is made. The /consider command is there to give me notification, before the next wave of attacks hits hopefully, if the NPC has forgotten about me or not.  If they regard you indifferently, you should be fine.  If they are Scowling, Ready to Attack, then your Feign Death has failed and you should stand back up immediately before their weapon delay runs out and they hit you for max damage as you lay prone before them.<br>
<br>
Until my monk was in the mid-20s, I rarely had occasion to need to "split" mobs.  Most of the creatures I chose to hunt were solitary, and I deliberately pulled them away from the paths of others of their kind if they were "social"(Creatures that are "social" are creatures who will join in a fight even if they were not attacked themselves.  Fire Beetles are a common type of "social" mob)  Since I had roughly 7 levels of practicing FD, by the time I needed to use it to split spawns, it was at master level.  Your experiences may be different if you don't have a master FD skill before starting to try to split spawns.  Many in the Monk community, and myself as well, highly reccommend having a Master skill level before trying.  This means level 20 at the earliest.  More example practice macros can be found at the end of this guide.<br>
<br>
Here is an example from some of my early days of learning how to split pulls.<br>
<br>
I've fought a lot in The Warrens. The King's room is essentially a large square that bulges where the throne room is. The King and the High Shaman often spawn together and it is necessary to split them if you can't take both together. Add the fact that some of the Kobold Elders, Pack Leaders or Huge Kobolds will still aggro on you at level 25, and it's kind of a difficult room to hold solo at the level I did it. Here is a link to a map of the room, and how I did it. <br>
<br>
http://www.eqatlas.com/warrensmap.html<br>
<br>
The King's room is number 11 on the map. The throne is pretty much exactly where the numbers are.<br>
<br>
The pathing in this room is pretty straightforward. It follows the walls for the most part, there is a path that crosses in front of the throne and a path that runs down the center of the room straight East from the throne and connects the cross-path and the path which runs North-South along the Eastern wall. The King spawns just West of the cross-line and just East of the throne(immediately to the right of the number 11 on the map, and the cross-line runs North-South just a little further East of the King's spawn point). The High Shaman spawns just North-East of the King.  In the case of The Warrens it is important to clear the room of all the Shaman-class mobs. Even the green mobs will heal the King or High Shaman if they are still up.  I also made rounds of all the Pack Elders, Huge Kobolds and others that might have been aggressive and add during my pull and killed them.  <br>
<br>
The way I split the King and High Shaman was to aggro both and run them around in the North-West wing of the throne room until the High Shaman began to cast a spell. As soon as he stopped to cast, I'd make a bee-line towards the South-East corner of the room, with the King hot on my heels. When I was hit by the spell I would immediately feign. The Shaman was in the North-West side of the room, left behind because he stopped chasing me to cast his spell and then lost interest after I feigned, so he would follow the path along the North side of the room back to the cross-line and then to his spawn point. However, the king was in the South-East corner, so he would hug the South wall until he got to the cross-line, then head North along it. This was plenty of space to tag the King again after feigning them off. The Shaman would stand in his spawn point blissfully unaware that I was killing the king.  His aggro radius at level 25 was about 15 feet or so, and his assist radius was a little larger, maybe 25 feet or so.<br>
<br>
When the king began to run, he would follow the walls to the North and East out the door, so he stayed away from the Shaman who would have healed him. After that I simply ran up to the Shaman and killed him at his spawn point. Without the king to back him up, he wasn't too hard.<br>
<br>
There is a second type of split pull you can do solo, it's far easier.  Sometimes when you pull a group of mobs they will stand over you after you feign and then each individual will wander off at different times.  Simply pull them all to you and then feign.  They will stand still for a certain amount of time, then take their paths back to spawn one at a time.  Stand back up after there are only one or two, or however many you can handle, left and engage it/them.  The dangrous thing about this type of split pulling is that often times the others will not have gone far enough and you will still be within their Assist Radius.  They will re-aggro, then if they are within another mob's Assist Radius, yet another mob will aggro and the chain will continue.  This is called Chain Aggro, and is deadly.   It's often better to take your time pulling and feigning several times without trying to engage the at all.  Just watch the pathing and amount of time between when each mob starts to wander back to their spawn point. This will help you determine what is the exact amount of time you need to stay feigned in order for enough of the group to have wandered far enough away for it to be safe to engage the others.<br>
<br>
To practice this type of pull I reccommend the Goblins in the Lake of Ill Omen.  <br>
<br>
http://www.eqatlas.com/kunark/lakeofillomenmap.html<br>
<br>
There are several ruined forts along the lake where Goblins hide behind the entranceways. Locations 6, and 9 on the map. If you pull one of these Goblins by the door, several others will come as well from further in the building.  Two and three at a time, sometimes with a Spirit Caller(shaman class mob).  Pull them towards the lakeshore and then feign on the beach.  They will sometimes wander far enough to not chain-aggro again, but sometimes when you stand back up the others have not gone far enough away and will come running back.  If you learn the pathing you can still split them, or pull a Sarnak to them and feign.  Once the Sarnak finishes off one or two of them(and dies to the third depending on the levels of each this will vary) you can mop up the rest.  The Goblins also tend to wander off at time intervals which allows them all to stay within each other's Assist Radius.  Practicing splitting pulls here will certainly give you the chance of seeing chain aggro in person.  A valuable experience.  Patience is required.  If they continue to chain-aggro, abort completely and let them return to spawn points and try again. Maybe pull to a different spot on the beach the next time and see if they take different paths back.<br>
<br>
Using a third-person view for this type of splitting is invaluable.  You can rarely accurately judge the distance the others have wandered if you don't use the third-person views.  I'd reccommend working on fighting using third-person views as much as possible, this will be of massive benefit both to you and your group.   Being able to see yourself, them behind you and the mobs you're pulling all at the same time is almost critical to the success of a high-end pull.<br>
<br>
For more detailed information on the Art of Pulling I highly reccommend the excellent <A HREF="http://pub38.ezboard.com/fmonklybusiness43508frm2.showMessage?topicID=291.topic">Guide to Advanced Pulling</A> by <b>LaotzuQigong</b><br>
<br>
Other places to practice splitting pulls are the Sarnaks in the Lake of Ill Omen, the City of Mist, Frogloks in Guk, Sol A & B, Cazic Thule, and Dalnir's Crypt.  Realistically, any zone where multiple creatures aggro on you can be used to practice splitting.  For practice purposes you could even run around and "tag" several NPCs to create a group to split.  This is kind of ridiculous when you consider the large number of zones where hostile NPCs are already organized into groups. <br>
<br>
At some point in your career be sure to visit a zone with many caster-type mobs.  Learning how to judge the timing of a Feign attempt in order to keep a spell from breaking it is something you must learn in person.  Running out of sight of a casting mob after they begin casting to keep them from casting over and over on you.  If you are out of line of sight, they will chase after you until they can see you again.  By leading them one curve at a time through corridors you can pull them to your group. You can also give yourself enough of a head start while they stand still casting to get out of line of sight and feign after the spells they're currently casting hit without worrying about them starting a new spell.<br>
<br>
<H4>Other Uses for Feign Death.</H4><br>
Feign Death is a remarkably flexible skill.  It can be used to help control aggro, to help travel, to save your life, and to aid in rescuing other groupmates.<br>
<br>
I have used it to run past creatures which would kill me and while they are chasing after me I would feign and they would wander back out of aggro range to their spawn points.  I could stand up and continue my journey.  When this is done repeatedly it is often called "feign-flopping" and allows monks to penetrate deep levels of dungeons or escape from such dungeons without magical aid.<br>
<br>
If many members of a group are killed during a bad fight, the monk can Feign Death and then after the mob has left, can drag his companions corpses to the zone line to be resurrected or looted.  This saves your groupmates the loss of valuable experience or equipment in especially dangerous zones.<br>
<br>
Aggro management with Feign Death is kind of tricky at high levels because mobs over level 32 do not have as high a chance of getting the memory-wipe effect, but there is still a chance.  Several monks choose to build a hotkey which produces an effect similar to the Evade ability of Rogues.<br>
<br>
/attack off<br>
/doability FD<br>
/con<br>
/Sit off<br>
/attack on<br>
<br>
If they regarded you indifferently with the con, then you probably lost some aggro and can stand back up to continue dealing damage.<br>
<br>
Feign Death can sometimes help you kill mobs you normally could not kill.  Pull a static spawn(one that does not wander) and fight it as long as you can.  Feign it off and as soon as it wanders out of aggro range begin to bind your wounds and recover your HP.  In this manner you can often regain HP faster than the Mob will and you can pull it again with you at half life and it already damaged.  Since you have healed more than it has, you can re-engage it and this extra bit of health will help you bring it lower than you could the first time. Repeat as necessary to whittle down it's life total.  Note that this is a very dangerous technique as the regeneration rate of mobs is extremely high and without a very high skill in Bind Wound you often will not be able to regain more life then the mob and the margin you are counting on will be negligible.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<H4>Appendix A</H4><br>
More practice macros for the Feign Death skill.<br>
Used by <b>Treign Pullah</b><br>
<br>
/do fd<br>
/sit off<br>
/do instill<br>
/do sneak<br>
/do sneak<br>
<br>
A nice practice macro that practices several skills at once. Can be used during long runs with minimal interruptions.<br>
<br>
Used by <b>Siji</b><br>
<br>
/pause 90,/doability FD<br>
/pause 90,/doability FD<br>
/pause 90,/doability FD<br>
/pause 90,/doability FD<br>
/stand<br>
<br>
A fairly impractical macro to use during runs, but very handy when waiting for a boat or while on a boat.  Be sure to keep this one in a hotkey bank you won't accidentally use during combat, this could take you out of the action for a while and really annoy your groupmates.<br>
<br>
<H4>Glossary of Terms Often Used in Discussions About Feign Death.</H4><br>
<b>Aggro and Assist Radius.</b><br>
<br>
The Aggro Radius is the minimum distance you must stay away from a hostile NPC to keep it from attempting to engage you.  <br>
<br>
The Assist Radius is the minimum distance you must be away from a second NPC which is "social" with the type of NPC you are fighting in order to keep it from attacking as well. <br>
<br>
Typically the Assist Radius is larger than the Aggro Radius.  If you need to be ten feet from a NPC to keep it from attacking you, you probably should allow 20 to 30 feet between the two of you and the nearest of it's fellows before attacking it if you do not wish to fight both.  The Assist Radius is the minimum distance you must keep both yourself and your opponent from any of it's fellows, even when it is running from you, to keep from having to fight both.<br>
<br>
The most important thing to remember about Aggro/Assist Radii is that they change constantly.  Depending on your level, your health, the mob you're fighting, your faction and dozens of other factors, these circles can be from tiny to enormous.  The Mansion of Unrest is famous for it's "lawn trash" which are usually low-level undead and Death Beetles which will join in a fight even if they themselves are green to the PCs.  If a PC is not engaged with a NPC, the death beetles leave them alone, but if they see an encounter, they hop in.  Only careful study of a zone and it's inhabitants will give you a feel for the aggro radii you will have to work around when pulling/splitting and fear kiting.  And you will have to re-learn this every level because these radii change.<br>
<br>
<b>Pathing.</b><br>
<br>
Think of paths like the highway/street system in real world cities.  Most of the time people stay on the roads, and if you're off the road for some reason and an emergency comes up(like being nearly beaten to death) the best chance you have is to get back to the road and hope someone else helps, or hope you can make it to some safe haven before you are slain.<br>
<br>
Players can pretty much wander wherever they want, but mobs typically follow pre-set paths.  When a zone is designed, paths are laid out that monsters will follow.  They may look like they are  wandering aimlessly, but in reality they are following these paths until something causes them  to leave it(something like chasing down an adventurer).  This is a restriction of the computer-based medium of the game.  If each monster were to have it's own sense of direction and be able to wander anywhere they pleased, the amount of programming and processing power they would require to keep from running off a cliff, wandering at the zone line trying to cross, or doing things like walking through lava, would be immense.   As a comprimise, there are, sometimes very complex, paths laid down that NPCs will follow. <br>
<br>
Sometimes adventurers engage NPCs on these paths, and another NPC wanders down it and joins the fight.  This can be deadly in many situations, and it is often better to provoke the NPC into following you to some goodly distance from the "path" and fighting it there.  If it is a monster which will attempt to run when it's life total gets low, it will turn around and head for the path again when it's life reaches a certain point.  If it reaches the path, it will again follow it in it's attempt to flee.  Knowing the movement patterns of the monsters you are hunting is extremely beneficial.  If they run straight into a camp of their fellows it could cause your death to run after them.  It would be wiser to pull them further out so they will be dead before they could reach their camp.  If you ever want to try the technique known as "Fear Kiting" using your Instill Doubt skill, knowing the pathing of the creatures you will be fighting becomes absolutely vital.  You should also study the pathing patterns of other creatures in the area to be sure there are none who will cross your path and join the fight on your enemy's side.  Often there are only a few paths in a zone and most monsters will re-use the same trail others used.  <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
