<br>
I agree about dalnir being a very good place to hone pulling abilities, before journeying to The Crypt of Dalnir I never really needed to use FD.  I would use it ocassionaly in the sarnak fort and goblin mines, but only when I picked up adds, not for splitting, as low lvl groups generaly can handle 2 mobs. When you arrive in Dalnir, you're in for a rude awakening if you have never feign pulled before. The casters will eat you alive if you pop FD just after you agro them as I tried. you have to anticipate how many spells are hitting you, and wait for effects (DoT landing, Nuke, slow, snare etc..) from each spell before feigning, this may require you to stand idle for a few sec while taking mele damage. This particular zone is taxing because there may be mobs casting on floors above/below you, so you basicaly ahve to guess at the number of mobs you agroed, and which are casting. This is the beginning of the many Educated Guessses you will encounter as a monk. Educated because you muct know what mobs you agroed and what class they are (each race/gender/size/name NPC in zone is a specific class in dalnir) and agro radius. <br>
<br>
Another feature not mentioned yet is chain pulling.This is used after lvl 35 when mobs remember you untill they return to spawn points. This is done by having a monk or shadowknight pulling a group of mobs to a set point, where another monk/shadowknight is feigned or a rogue is hidden. the monk feigns off the mobs. The other monk/sk or rogue pops up when one (or two, depending on how many group wants) mob is left. This can also be acomplished by having a caster or archer hit the remaining mob when signaled by the monk on the first leg, but it is more dangerous for a non-feigner to do second leg since if they go early they cannot lose agro from the ensuing train.<br>
The traditional chain pulling methods are thrown out in Velious (and Luclin?) since mobs all return at once to their spawn points/paths, making chain pulling impossible. Usually, my groups will have a SK/necro (dangerous for necro...) snare one mob and wait for all (including snared mob, who will trail behind the others) to get to them, where the second leg of the chain is waiting and feign. Necro will need to burn HS for this. When the mobs go back to spawn points, snared mob will be left behind somewhat, if you pulled it far enough from the bind point, it will be easily single pulled. This is hampered by unsnareable mobs and resists though, and is time-comsuming most times.<br>
<br>
There is probably more to pulling I don't know yet, as I managed to get through nearly 54 levels without knowing I could put skills in macros.... thanks for the input on that. I'm not going to venture into calling this a comprehensive guide, but it is a start for young pullers looking to earn their keep. this, along with the information above, should take you up to 50's imho. <p>Greetings!</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#778899><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub38.ezboard.com/uxaylintunare.showPublicProfile?language=EN>XaylinTunare</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Monk-in-Training</span><br>  Posts: 76<br> <font color=#8b1a1a>(12/31/01 1:07:38 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fmonklybusiness43508frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=668.topic&index=19>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: A start on the Feign Death guide we need.</span><hr size=1> &lt;&lt;Sometimes when you FD and stand right back up you cant move, the fix is to sit and then stand again.&gt;&gt;<br>
